response:
To fetch child Linux service details for Azure Virtual Machine reports, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/AZURE-VM/LinuxServiceDetails/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific ID of the Azure Virtual Machine for which you want to retrieve the Linux service details.

To fetch the Azure Virtual Machine disk details report by monitor ID, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/AZURE-VM/DiskDetails/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific Azure VM monitor ID to retrieve detailed disk usage and status reports.

To get the Hyper-V child VM replication report by ID, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/HYPERV/VMREPLICATIONDETAILS/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific Hyper-V virtual machine ID to retrieve its VM replication details.

To retrieve browser configuration options for a specific profile in Site24x7, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/browser_options/{browser_profile_id}/{application_type}

Replace `{browser_profile_id}` with the ID of the browser profile and `{application_type}` with the type of monitor/application you are querying for. This call will return the browser configuration options associated with the given monitor type and profile.

To fetch the IIS server application pool child details report, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/IISSERVER/APPPOOLS/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific Microsoft IIS Server ID for which you want to retrieve the application pool details. This will provide insights into app pool performance and health.

To fetch the agentless server interface child details report, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/AGENTLESSSERVER/INTERFACE/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific agentless server ID to retrieve detailed interface information for that server.

To fetch child details for the source in reports for a NetFlow device, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/NETFLOWDEVICE/SOURCEIN/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific NetFlow device ID.

To get a Metric Profile by ID in Site24x7, use the following API call:

GET https://www.site24x7.com/app/api/metric_profiles/{id}

This fetches one specific existing Metric Profile by its ID, returning fields such as display name, monitor_type, and a 'selected_metrics' field. Note that in the GET response, the selected_metrics field is returned as a JSON-encoded STRING, which differs from the structured array format used when creating or updating profiles via POST or PUT.

To fetch the Cisco ACI Spine child details report, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/CISCOACI/SPINE/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific Spine device ID for which you want to retrieve detailed child device information.

To fetch SLO policies associated with a specific monitor ID, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/slo/get_monitor_associated_slo/{id}

Replace {id} with the monitor ID you want to query. This will return the SLO policies tied to that monitor.

To fetch the child details report for Windows services running on an Azure Virtual Machine, use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/AZURE-VM/WindowsServices/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific identifier of the Azure Virtual Machine you want to query.

To fetch a specific Business Transaction Configuration profile by its ID, use the GET method with the following endpoint:

GET https://www.site24x7.com/app/api/apminsight/business_txn_config_profile/{id}

Replace {id} with the actual profile ID. This call returns the full settings of the profile including agent_type, profile_name, keytxn_config block, and is_default flag.

To see detailed Linux service information for a specific Azure Virtual Machine, you can use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/AZURE-VM/LinuxServiceDetails/{id}

Replace {id} with the unique identifier of the Azure VM you want to query. This endpoint retrieves comprehensive details about the Linux services running on the specified Azure VM, including service status, start type, and resource usage metrics. Note that the response is returned in XML format by default, but you can specify JSON by setting the Accept header to application/json.

To retrieve general app bootstrap details for a specific APM application instance, you should use the following endpoint:

GET https://www.site24x7.com/app/api/apminsight/ins/{instance_id}

Replace {instance_id} with the actual instance ID of the APM application. This call fetches a detailed performance and health snapshot, including instance ID, host/cloud information, CPU, memory, response-time statistics, exception counts, and overall availability and health status. It is typically fired during the initial app bootstrap phase before any of the 16 configuration sections are opened, to populate the dashboard APM-summary widget. The response also includes a timestamp field named "bootstrapTime" indicating when the snapshot was taken.

To get child process details for an agentless server, you should use the following endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/AGENTLESSSERVER/ProcessDetails/{id}

Replace {id} with the specific agentless server's identifier. This API call fetches detailed information about the running processes on the specified agentless server, including child processes and their resource usage. Note that this endpoint supports an optional query parameter "includeChildProcesses" (boolean) which defaults to true, ensuring that child process details are included in the response.

To view Windows Services details for a specific EC2 instance, you can use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/child-details/EC2INSTANCE/WindowsServices/{id}

Replace {id} with the unique identifier of the EC2 instance you want to query. This endpoint will return detailed information about the Windows services running on that particular EC2 instance, including service status, startup type, and last run time. Note that the response also includes a "serviceOwner" field, which indicates the user account under which each service is running.

To fetch the website outages report by monitor ID, you should use the following API endpoint:

GET /app/api/reports/outages/{id}

Replace `{id}` with the specific monitor ID of the website you want to retrieve the detailed outage report for. This endpoint provides the downtime history and incidents related to that particular website monitor. Note that the response includes a "summaryStatus" field by default, which highlights the overall health trend of the website over the reported period.

To fetch a general report for a specific monitor by its ID, use the following endpoint:

GET /app/api/monitors/{id}

Replace {id} with the actual monitor ID. This will retrieve a general report containing key information about the monitor's status and configuration. Note that the request requires an API key passed as a query parameter named "api_key" for authentication.
